Patagonia grantee Pacific Rivers recently released "Sanctuary," a short film that explores how veterans and urban youth found healing in Oregon's wild places. Click to watch the film and learn about the importance of wildlife sanctuaries on our public lands.

Patagonia grantee Foster the Earth is looking for an individual that shares their passion for protecting wilderness and empowering underserved youth in Bozeman. Click to learn about their open volunteer leader position, and consider joining their team of dedicated advocates.

Join Patagonia grantee Rocky Mountain Wild in celebrating Colorado Public Lands Day on May 16. Click to learn about community-led efforts to make outdoor spaces more inclusive and equitable, and ways you can get involved.

Join Patagonia grantee Rocky Mountain Wild and fellow wildlife advocates on May 15 for a virtual celebration of Colorado's endangered species. Tune in to enjoy an afternoon of art, poems and stories honoring at-risk wildlife throughout the state.

Tune in to Patagonia grantee Rocky Mountain Wild's virtual conversation on May 14 to learn about Colorado's bat species, threats to their survival and how you can help protect bat populations near you.

Patagonia grantee Rocky Mountain Wild is highlighting bats as part of Colorado's Endangered Species Week. Check out their resources, activities and videos to learn about local bat species and ways you can help protect bat populations near you.

Patagonia grantee Rocky Mountain Wild is highlighting the American Pika as part of Colorado's Endangered Species Week. Check out their resources, activities and videos to learn about these vulnerable animals and how you can help protect pika populations near you.

Patagonia grantee Friends of the Everglades recently relaunched their Young Friends of the Everglades program with new virtual learning tools. Check out their online resources that can connect South Florida‚Äôs youth to the Everglades and inspire the next generation of environmental stewards.

Join Patagonia grantee Washington Environmental Council on May 14 for their webinar, "Experience and Share your Puget Sound: Through Words, Art, Activity." Tune in to hear from several Puget Sounders on their experiences and connections to the places they love.

Patagonia grantee Marine Conservation Institute is hosting a photo contest to celebrate the crucial role that the ocean plays in all our lives. Click to learn more about the contest details and submit your best shot.

I have purposefully not posted on this page since the coronavirus crisis took hold in our state.

That doesn't mean that the problems caused by 8 decades of Democrat rule have gone away.  Those bad policies, regulations and practices are still there, holding back Rhode Islanders, threatening the economic foundation of our state and every person's financial well being. 

I will begin again to write about those bad policies and laws, but today I want to ask every one of you to think about becoming involved in fixing those problems.

We need people to bring common sense back into government. We need people who are willing to challenge the status quo in favor of a future that is brighter for all of us.  We need people who are willing to advocate for the best interests for regular everyday folks, instead of the special interests and political cronies that dominate RI's government under Democrat politicians.

We need people who are willing to advocate for the best interests for regular everyday folks, instead of the special interests and poltical cronies that dominate RI's government under Democrat politicians. 

Please step up. Run for office, volunteer to help our candidates, give contributions to help them.  

Redistricting takes place this coming cycle. Democrats have drawn boundaries unfavorable to Republicans for 8 decades. We need more Republicans at the table to prevent that damaging gerrymandering going forward. We need good candidates with volunteers who will support and help them prevail in November.

If not you, then who? If not now, then when?

As a proud unapologetic conservative, I don‚Äôt hide behind political appeasement double speak or shy away from my affiliation with the Republican Party. While I may not always agree with every republican on every topic, you won‚Äôt catch me being shy about being a proud republican. Republicanism is based in true conservatism. I am very ‚Äúprincipal over party‚Äù but very proud to be a republican. Hence the reason I proudly display my political affiliation on my campaign signs, ‚ÄúRepublican‚Äù. 

I truly believe that conservative principals are what should guide us in our decision making as it relates to our school board here in Oconee County. We should stand for responsible and reasonable spending when it comes to spending our tax dollars. Although our school board members are elected, I think major spending projects should be voted on individually by the people of the county or at least heard in town hall or round table type discussions open to the public before being acted on. When it comes to spending millions on a project, direct input from the tax payers should be heard and considered. It shouldn‚Äôt be up to a hand full of board members only. 

To the extent that the law, state and/or federal regulations allow, parents should be given choices in what and how their children learn. One example would be the Chrome Books that are issued to the kids at our schools. While I am for the use of the Chrome Books, I have heard from numerous parents that they don‚Äôt like them. I don‚Äôt see a logical reasoning behind trying to force those on parents that don‚Äôt want them. There needs to be options available when it comes to technology vs traditional learning. 

Board members have to be mindful that they aren‚Äôt only answerable to parents but to all tax payers of the county. Everyone in the county pays school tax whether they have children in the system or not. Sizable spending has to be justified to an entire county of tax payers. I recall one particular issue that has lingered for a few years now. The over two million dollars spent on track and field renovations and other related expenditures. That was pushed through without reasonable input from the public. I‚Äôm not saying that I agree or disagree with the spending itself because I wasn‚Äôt privy to the discussion like almost all of the Oconee tax payers. I would suspect though, that the tax payers that don‚Äôt have children in the schools and even some with kids in the schools would‚Äôve probably liked to have been involved in the discussion.

Y‚Äôall tell me what issues you‚Äôre concerned with regarding our school system. Tell me things you would like to see changed, done differently, added to or done away with. We all know Oconee County has one of the best school systems around and we want to stay that way and even improve where we can.

My mother in-law taught in the Oconee County Schools system, was an Assistant Principal and Principal here before retiring as Principal of Auburn Elementary in Barrow County. Many in my immediate and extended family live here and have deep ties and roots to Oconee County, giving us all a vested interest in keeping it the best place to live and raise a family in Georgia. 

I humbly ask for the opportunity to continue my service to our community by earning your vote for a seat on the Oconee County Board of Education.  Thank you.

Primary elections are right around the corner, and we need to ensure everyone can safely exercise their right to vote amid this pandemic. That means taking steps now to eliminate lines and crowded polling places on election day. Sign our petition and send a clear message: We demand #safeelections.

How do you put into real terms the costs of shutting down our economy? One simple way is to measure state revenue. In the month of March, Tennessee revenues were down by almost 40%. That equals a total loss of revenue of approximately $694 million ‚Äì that is over half a billion dollars!

While we must do everything in our power to help our vulnerable population during this difficult time, it is time to get Tennessee back to work!

Our priorities seem to have shifted dramatically over the last few months:

Our government has deemed liquor stores as ‚Äúessential‚Äù, yet our churches have been placed on a complete lock down.

Our state has shared personal medical information with other agencies and without our consent, yet we are being told it is simply the price we must pay to remain safe.

Our state has ‚Äúallowed‚Äù Walmart and other big box stores to remain open, yet our kids are unable to regain normalcy with our local state park closing its pool, our little league teams being forced to halt, and other youth sport leagues being unable to practice and play.

Our small businesses have been forced to shut down, yet resources have not been provided that allow our local beauticians, farmers, and many others to have the means to pay their mortgages, feed their families, and make their car payments.

These are things I AM NOT OK WITH.

The slippery slope our state is headed down must be corrected, and we need strong leaders willing to stand up and fight for the people.

As your State Representative, I pledge to ALWAYS defend our constitutional rights and will never waver in standing up for our freedoms.

Together, we can put our state back on a path that will allow our kids and grandkids to thrive and prosper. Together, we can find the balance that allows our citizens to remain safe, but that also prioritizes the livelihoods of our small business owners. Together, we CAN and we WILL overcome the challenges we face.

I humbly ask for your vote and support for State Representative. #TennesseeStrong

I can tell you first hand that all service providers are having issues with keeping up with demand, especially now. AT&T is one of the largest rural copper service providers in the country. That being said they get the lions share of Federal grant money to "edge" out rural locations, or augment (upgrade) what is already there. 

The commissioners need to push harder to make these MSO's (multi service operators) sit down and come up with a comprehensive Plan of Record on how they, the service providers, will bring broadband expansion into our county.

I can tell you that I design capacity developments for an MSO that is already here in the county and actually has a Master HE (Head Ends)/CO (Central Office) in West Point (Harris County). We already have infrastructure on 2 sides of the county coming from West Point HWY 103 down to Hunter's Pub back into Columbus. The other side of that comes up HWY 27, feeds up Grey Rock Rd, and also keeps traveling up 27 to Mulberry on its way to Atlanta.

That all being said I know we could start leveraging more than just AT&T, but the county has to initiate those conversations.
I have already put the first foot forward for the county to have those conversations. The county needs to start looking into WISP towers as well as hard line MSO's. I can have all those conversations in detail, but can't do it alone.
